 to criminal justice, truth-telling, and overcriminalization, the authors provide important insights into often overlooked practices that admit persons to criminal justice. It is essential reading for scholars, students, and policy makers in the fields of socio-legal studies, sociology, criminology, law and society, and post/colonial studies. Contributors: Dale A. Ballucci, Martin A. French, Aaron Henry, Bryan R. Hogeveen, Dawn Moore, George Pavlich, Marcus A. Sibley, Rashmee Singh, Amy Swiffen, Matthew P. Unger, Elise Wohlbold, Andrew Woolford  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCrimezCanadaxSociological aspects. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzCanada. 0aCriminal procedurezCanada. 7aLAW / Criminal Procedure.2bisacsh  aLaw & Society / Postcolonial Studies.1 aBallucci, Dale A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrench, Martin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrench, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenry, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogeveen, Bryan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPavlich, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPavlich, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSibley, Marcus A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSingh, Rashmee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwiffen, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnger, Matthew P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnger, Matthew P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go